# UI Layout Guardrails

## Core requirement

- Treat horizontal page scroll as a bug. Vertical scroll is allowed.
- All new or changed UI must be usable on mobile and desktop.

## Horizontal overflow policy

- Do not rely on page-level horizontal scrolling (`body`, root app shell, or page wrappers).
- Before adding width, prefer stacking/wrapping (`flex-col`, `grid-cols-1`) and truncation.
- If content is inherently wide (large table/calendar/timeline), confine overflow to a local panel with `overflow-x-auto` and clear visual boundaries.
- Keep root shells constrained with `min-w-0` on flex children.

## Mobile-complete behavior

- Every feature/action available on desktop must remain reachable on mobile.
- Desktop sidebars must have a mobile equivalent (drawer/sheet/menu), not hidden-only nav.
- Interactive targets should be touch-friendly and visible without horizontal panning.

## Implementation defaults

- Favor viewport-aware layouts: sticky headers/actions, collapsible sections, tabs/segmented controls.
- Avoid fixed widths that exceed mobile viewport unless inside a scoped overflow container.

## Validation checklist for UI changes

- [ ] No horizontal page scroll at 320, 375, and 390 widths.
- [ ] Primary actions and navigation are reachable on mobile.
- [ ] Any necessary horizontal overflow is scoped to a component-level container.
- [ ] Desktop and mobile navigation paths are equivalent for key routes.
